{
  "text": "Imaging decision-making for the TLS must start with a thorough clinical examination. This includes an assessment of the patient's conscious state and a decision as to whether he/she is evaluable or not, as is a fundamental component of accepted cervical spine decision rules. However, in a recent prospective observational study of 3065 patients undergoing TLS imaging in 13 participating centres, Inaba et al., [CITATION_1] demonstrated that clinical examination alone is insufficient to determine the need for imaging of the TLS [CITATION_2] and that the addition of a clinical decision rule incorporating age and high-risk mechanism of injury ( Figure 1 ) improved the sensitivity for detecting clinically significant TLS injury from 78.4 to 98.9%. In Inaba's study, patients with neurological deficit due to cervical spine fractures were excluded; however, concomitant spinal fractures without neurological deficit were not mentioned as included in the regression analyses. This variable may need to be considered in order for Inaba's clinical decision rule to become widely accepted.",
